   173→
   174→### USAGE PATTERN IN ANIMATION LOOPS
   175→
   176→```typescript
   177→// In InfiniteCanvas.tsx - Animation loop reads from store directly
   178→const animate = () => {
   179→  // Read state from store (always current, no stale closures)
   180→  const state = canvasStore.getState();
   181→  const anim = state.viewport.animation;
   182→
   183→  if (!anim.isAnimating) {
   184→    return;
   185→  }
   186→
   187→  const elapsed = Date.now() - anim.startTime;
   188→  const progress = Math.min(elapsed / anim.duration, 1);
   189→  const easedProgress = Easing.quadOut(progress);
   190→
   191→  // Update via dispatch (not setState)
   192→  canvasStore.dispatch(
   193→    canvasActions.viewport.updateAnimation({ camera: clamped })
   194→  );
   195→
   196→  if (progress < 1) {
   197→    requestAnimationFrame(animate);
   198→  }
   199→};
   200→```
   201→
   202→### VERIFICATION: VERIFIED
   203→- No stale closure issues in momentum/zoom animations
   204→- State reads are always synchronous via `getState()`
   205→- Dispatches trigger React re-renders only for subscribed selectors
   206→
   207→### CRITICAL MIGRATION NOTES
   208→1. NEVER use `useState` for animation-related state
   209→2. Use `canvasStore.getState()` in animation loops, not React hooks
   210→3. `metadata: false` is critical for 60fps performance (disables object allocations)
   211→4. Session cache policy means state resets on page refresh
